1. Two sum:
Given an array of integers nums and an integer target, return indices of the two numbers such that they add up to target.
Input: nums = [2,7,11,15], target = 9
Output: [0,1]
Explanation: Because nums[0] + nums[1] == 9, we return [0, 1].

      
Idea behind: add 2 numbers will give a sum so iterate each element and subtract with sum.
      to get the value use map since in next iteration it will be avaiable 

    sum of two numbers a+b = c
        here c known , need to find a+b 
          b = c-a or a = c-b 

  Logic:
  1. iterate each element 0 to arr.length
  2. subtract element from target and  check in map 
  3. put the result in map with key as cuurent num  and value as index
  4. map is for finding the another element and its index if its exist then return both elements index (a, b).
          
Solution :
  class Solution {
    public int[] twoSum(int[] nums, int target) {

       Map<Integer,Integer> mapKey= new HashMap<Integer,Integer>();
        for(int i=0; i<nums.length ; i++){
            int val= target-nums[i];
            if(mapKey.containsKey(val)){
               return new int [] { mapKey.get(val), i};
            }
            mapKey.put(nums[i],i);
           
        }
        return new int[] {};
    }
}
